    summary: `Salyan is a peaceful hill district headquarters in Karnali Province, set at 1,530 metres amid the mid-western hills of Nepal. Known for its panoramic views of the Dhaulagiri and Karnali highlands, traditional market town atmosphere, and the nearby Kalimati viewpoint, Salyan offers an authentic window into mid-western Nepali hill culture away from the main trekking circuits.`,
    story: `<p>Salyan Khalanga — the district headquarters of Salyan — occupies a prominent ridge at 1,530 metres in the mid-western hills of Karnali Province. With coordinates placing it centrally within the broader Karnali basin, the town commands views north to the Dhaulagiri and Karnali highland ranges and south across the rolling hills descending toward the Terai. The district itself covers 1,462 square kilometres of diverse terrain from subtropical river valleys to temperate highland forests.</p><p>Salyan has historically been a crossroads district — connected to Dang in the south, Surkhet to the west, and Rolpa and Rukum to the north and east. The weekly market at the district headquarters draws traders and farmers from a wide catchment, and the town has a lively bazaar culture characteristic of Nepal's mid-western administrative centres. The local cuisine features the distinctive dishes of the Khas-Arya communities of the mid-western hills — dhedo (buckwheat porridge), local varieties of fermented greens, and home-distilled spirits.</p><p>The Kalimati viewpoint near the district headquarters offers panoramic vistas of the surrounding mountain country, and rhododendron forests bloom spectacularly in March and April on the hillsides above the town. Several small temples and religious sites dot the town and its surrounding villages, reflecting the deep Hindu traditions of the Salyan communities.</p><p>As part of Nepal's developing road network, Salyan has become increasingly connected in recent years, with a road linking it to the East-West Highway at Lamahi in Dang. This improved connectivity is gradually opening the district to domestic tourists from the Terai cities, though international visitor numbers remain minimal — making it genuinely off-beat for foreign travellers seeking an unmediated experience of mid-western Nepali hill life.</p>`,
