    story: `<p>Established in January 2010, the Gaurishankar Conservation Area encompasses 2,179 km² of Himalayan landscape across Dolakha, Ramechhap, and Sindhupalchok districts in Bagmati Province. The conservation area takes its name from Gaurishankar (7,134 m), the towering peak that dominates the northern skyline — a mountain so sacred in Hindu tradition that it is believed to be the combined abode of Shiva (Shankar) and his consort Parvati (Gauri). The mountain was not permitted to be climbed until 1979, such was its religious significance.</p><p>The centrepiece of the conservation area is the Rolwaling Valley — one of Nepal's most remote and dramatically beautiful glacier valleys, stretching westward from the Tibetan border toward the Tesi Lapcha Pass. The valley harbours the sacred Tsho Rolpa glacial lake (4,580 m), one of Nepal's largest and fastest-growing glacial lakes, which has expanded significantly due to climate-change-driven glacial retreat and is now closely monitored for outburst flood risk. Above the lake, the Tesi Lapcha Pass (5,755 m) provides a challenging high-altitude crossing into the Khumbu region.</p><p>The Tamang and Sherpa communities of the Rolwaling Valley maintain a living Buddhist culture shaped by centuries of relative isolation. The small monastery at Na village and the seasonal high pastures above it preserve traditions of yak herding and high-mountain Buddhism that are rapidly disappearing elsewhere. The valley's wildlife is exceptional — snow leopard, Himalayan tahr, red panda, and over 250 bird species inhabit the diverse altitudinal zones from 968 m to 7,181 m.</p><p>The conservation area receives a modest but growing number of trekkers, particularly on the Rolwaling-Everest crossing route and the Gaurishankar base camp approaches. Its relative remoteness compared to Langtang and Everest makes it a prized destination for experienced trekkers seeking solitude and genuine Himalayan adventure.</p>`,
